(\Longleftarrow ) Suppose [\mathbb {F}(\alpha ) : \mathbb {F}] is finite. Define
\begin {split}T\colon &\mathbb {F}(\alpha )\to \mathbb {F}(\alpha )\\ &x\mapsto \alpha  x\end {split}
Then T is a linear operator on a finite-diumensional vector space. So it has a minimal polynomial as a linear operator. Let m(x) be this minimal polynomial for T. We find m(T) sends x\mapsto  m(\alpha )x, but we also know m(\alpha )=0 by the Cayley-Hamilton theorem.

