\mathbb {F}=L_{0}\subset  L_{1}\subset …\subset  L_{n}=\mathbb {L}
where G_{n-i}=\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (L_{n} / L_{i}). Then
\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (L_{i+1}/L_{i})\cong \frac {\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\mathbb {L} /L_{i})}{\mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\mathbb {L} /L_{i+1})}=\frac {G_{n-i}}{G_{n-i-1}}
is cyclic. Then we see each element \alpha \in \mathbb {L} lies in a Root Extension, hence p(x) is solvable by radicals.

Let \Bbbk  be a Number Field. Any ideal I\mathrel {\trianglelefteq }\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk } factors into a product
I=P_{1}^{e_{1}}(…)P_{r}^{e_{r}}
of distinct prime ideals P_{i}\mathrel {\trianglelefteq }\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk }, and this factorization is unique up to rearrangement.

Let \Bbbk  be a Number Field, let (p)\mathrel {\trianglelefteq }\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk } be a principal ideal of the algebraic integers of \Bbbk , suppose we have the prime factorization of (p) into
(p)=P_{1}^{e_{1}}(…)P_{r}^{e_{r}}
where P_{i}\mathrel {\trianglelefteq }\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk } are distinct prime ideals.

Let P\mathrel {\trianglelefteq }\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk } be a prime ideal over p\in \mathbb {Z}. Then the Decomposition Subgroup of \mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {Q}) is
D_{P}=\{\sigma \in \mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\Bbbk  / \mathbb {Q})\mid  \sigma (P)=P\}
the elements of the Galois group leaving P invariant.

If \sigma \in  D_{P}, then it induces a field automorphism
\begin {split}\overline {\sigma }\colon &\mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk }/P\to \mathcal {O}_{\Bbbk }/P\\ &x+P\mapsto \sigma (x)+P\end {split}
Therefore there is a map D_{P}\to \mathop {\textrm {Gal}}\nolimits (\mathbb {F}_{q}/\mathbb {F}_{p}) sending \sigma \mapsto \overline {\sigma }.

Let \Bbbk  / \mathbb {F} be a field extension. Let S_{1}\subseteq  S_{2}\subseteq …\subseteq \Bbbk  be a tower of algebraically independent sets. Then
S=\bigcup _{i=1}^{\infty }S_{i}
is algebraically independent.
